abstract.value: Sarah Jacobson was born in Norwalk, Connecticut in 1971. Her family eventually moved to Edina, Minnesota, where Jacobson graduated from high school. As a teenager, Sarah Jacobson was drawn to the independent film and music scene in Minneapolis. She attended the San Francisco Art Institute where she met her mentor, George Kuchar. While still in film school, Sarah Jacobson wrote, produced and directed her first films including, <emph render="italic">The Adventures of Sweet Miss: The Disco Years</emph> and <emph render="italic">I Was A Teenage Serial Killer</emph>. Shortly after graduating from College, Jacobson, wrote, directed and produced her first feature-length film, <emph render="italic">Mary Jane's Not A Virgin Anymore</emph>, which screened internationally. The Sarah Jacobson Papers include production materials from her independent film projects, freelance writing, activism work, teaching and commercial work. Material types include film production materials, writing, clippings, audio-cassettes, video recordings, films, flyers, fanzines and artifacts.

p.value: Identification of item, date; Sarah G. Jacobson Papers; MSS 157; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University.
Donated by Ruth Jacobson in 2005; additional accretions were donated in 2008 and 2018. The accession numbers associated with these gifts are 2004.157, 2008.157, and 2018.079.

The 2018 accretion contains personal notebooks from 1987 to 2004 as well as her published work on modern film and photography from mulitiple Sundance Film Festivals and the production of <emph render="italic">Mary Jane's Not A Virgin Anymore</emph>.

Scope and Contents

This accretion includes production materials from Sarah G. Jacobson's independent film projects and freelance writing. The bulk of the material relates to Jacobson's professional career, primarily the production of her films Mary Jane's Not A Virgin Anymore and I Was A Teenage Serial Killer. These materials consist of notebooks, photographs, correspondence, 68 video recordings, and 8 born-digital CD-R's from her directing projects, as well as collections of Jacobson's published writing. Photography from the production of Mary Jane's Not A Virgin Anymore, multiple Sundance Film Festivals, and a launch party of a music video for the British punk band Fluffy are also present. Jacobson's freelance writing on modern film from 1995 to 1998 published in fanzines, underground film and music publications such as Filth and Film Threat, as well as commercial publications Sassy and YM represent her contributions to film journalism. In addition, this accretion includes classwork and notebooks from 1987 to 2004.
